title: heat pro repman heater for preventing warping.

description.text:
Using 3 pieces of acrylic, 1 6inch by 6 inch board and 25 to 30 220ohm resistors i made this heater plate. you can make it too! - i soldered one end of the resistors to the copper board, applied a thin layer of tape to the area across that was not soldered, and then soldered the other end to a wire . the red wire was positive, the copper plate was negative, i then soldered the copper board with a black wire, and then taped several times over the copper side with the resistors several times to allow heat to stay in. using the resistor values is ok, a method that uses 330ohms is used to keep telescopes from fogging at night. the idea is to provide enough energy in heat that can be dissipated safely. the soldered end of the resistor transfers heat to the copper board. the copper acts as a heat spreader, and the pcb acts as a good stick layer for thermal plastic. I also have a video here:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pDEkp3ym1TE

you need a 6 inch by 6 inch copper board. 4 oz of alumilite poly urethane (high temp cure plastic0
25-30 220ohm resisters (not any lower that this value, and max voltage 14volts!)
a cnc machine to cut out parts. the file is what i used to cut thru 3 .1 inch layers of acrylic stacked on top of each other and mounted. 
the top acrylic sheet will have a 6inch by 6 inch square. use grinder and re size circuit board to fit into this square. 
add in resistors evenly spaces, although since copper spreads heat it should not need to be exact.  
once device is wired, then pour urethane to keep resistors safe and to keep heat in. 
also the part that faces out is the pcb side. the copper side is is inside and coated with urethane

This is an approximation of a wooden recorder. This recorder really works (tested in PLA), but the sound of course is not as good as the original wooden recorder.

To build a single recorder, following printed items are required:

RecorderTopWithoutCore.stl
RecorderTopCore.stl
BottomFlutePart1.stl
BottomFlutePart2.stl
BottomFlutePart3.stl

If one has a build platform that is higher then 230 mm, it is possible to use "BottomFlute.stl" instead of "BottomFlutePart1-3".

Improvements compared to the previous design:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1412604

  • much improved print-ability (almost no post processing required)
  • improved sound quality (by improved shape of windpipe and labium)

The variable "PRINTABLE = 0" can be set to "PRINTABLE = 1". If the variable is set to "1", the stl's are rendered with corrections that compensate the imperfections of my own printer. Some holes will be printed slightly enlarged, so that the dimensions will be spot on.

To adjust dimensions for other printers following variables can be changed:

  • correction_r_innercore = PRINTABLE ? 0.15 : 0.05; // clearance of "RecorderTopCore.stl" into "RecorderTopWithoutCore.stl"
  • correction_r_bottom = PRINTABLE ? 0.15 : 0.00; // clearance of "BottomFlutePart1.stl" into "RecorderTopWithoutCore.stl"
  • correction_r_partcut = PRINTABLE ? 0.10 : 0.05; // clearance of "BottomFlutePart2.stl" into "BottomFlutePart1.stl" and clearance of "BottomFlutePart3.stl" into "BottomFlutePart2.stl"
  • correction_h_partoverlap = PRINTABLE ? 1.00 : 0.05; // clearance in z-direction of part into another part; this is not likely to be a critical dimension

description.text:
This is a custom keyboard tent git for the ergodox ez keyboard. They sell a tent kit with the keyboard but I needed more angle with the keyboard so I designed this.
It is based loosely on the Freestyle2 ascent keyboard tent kit but with changes to make the design more printer friendly.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

MakerBot Replicator (5th Generation)

Rafts:

Yes

No

Resolution:

.2 mm

Notes:

The base parts and stands can be printed in .3 mm but I kept having issues with the hinges when printing the keyboard mounts at the larger resolution.

Keyboard moves/slides while typing

I have had some issues with the tent kit sliding on my desk. I have a smooth surface on my desk and ended up putting double sided tape under the bottom plates to hold it in place better. It isn't a problem for me when I use an XTrackPad but YMMV depending on your desk surface.

Hinge pieces don't fit

I printed 2 sets of hinge pins (1.75mm and 1.25mm). It depends on what resolution you print your other parts and how well the prints turned out. I didn't have to file the hinges at all but I cut the extra length off the pins so they wouldn't stick out. It may also be good to put a dab of hot glue on the end to keep the pin in but I haven't had a problem yet.

My 5 year old daughter has been watching me 3D print for most of her life, so it was no surprise when she asked me if her dolls could have a 3D printer of their own. I originally intended to just print her one of the little 3D printer keychains I've seen here on Thingiverse, but in the end decided to do something a little more personal. With nothing more than a ruler and an evening in OpenSCAD, I created the PrintrBot Mini.

The PB Mini is a roughly 1/5th scale model of the PrintrBot Simple Metal, which looked about right to go with her large Barbie and Ken dolls. I didn't go into any detail on the extruder at this scale, but did think it was important to show the hotend and autolevel sensor, since those are the most obvious visual features (and the most colorful).

Update 12/2/16: Bring hotend and sensor to edge of arm to help with overhang

Base

Simple print; I personally switched from black to silver while printing the base to get the two-tone effect, but you could just as easily paint the "tower" to get a similar effect.

Arm

The arm prints with no support, though the overhang over the hotend and sensor might be a bit much for some machines. All the detail painting is required on this piece, you could skip it and just leave it as-is, but I don't think the visual effect would be as good.

Bed

This is just a rectangle; either paint it or print it in a different color than the base. I find that the blue PLA from PrintrBot is almost the exact same color as 3M painters tape, so it worked great.

The SCAD file is a wreck; I wanted to do something properly parametric so you could render it at an arbitrary scale, but in the end it's pretty hacky.

I really wanted to do something more impressive with the fan, but in the end it is just a flat panel. Could probably paint some detail on the outside if you wanted, but I figured any kind of printed effect (like trying to print tiny "blades") would get lost at this scale.

In terms of usability, the hole in the arm to accept the tower is definitely too small, and I had to use a file to widen it up before the arm would smoothly slide on it.

description.text: If you're trying to throw together a Botmobile or similar RC setup on the cheap, you can make your own brushed DC speed controller out of the guts of an old servo.  I modified the guts out of a Hobby King TGY-S4505B servo for Thingiverse user Luis to use with his Botmobile and turtle shell racer (seen here).

All you need to do is remove the controller of a standard servo and replace the potentiometer with two equal value resistors (typically 2.2k, but higher values should be OK) and hook up the brushed motor you want to control in place of the servo's DC motor. The DC motor you hook up should turn forward or backward at a speed proportional to the throttle on your particular RC setup. If you've modified a servo for continuous rotation this should be very familiar to you because that's essentially what you've done, you're just not using the mechanics of the servo. You can find some more pics and a write up on my blog here: http://www.built-to-spec.com/blog/?p=768

description.text:
I always wanted to build a proper iPhone holder for my motorcycle because buying a dedicated motorcycle sat nav is really expensive and there is usable software on the marked that complement the capabilities of an iphone well.

So, after I bought my Triumph Speed Triple 1050 I drove it back home and instantly got lost on the way. I hated to get off the bike, pull the iPhone out, check directions and do that same thing all over again for a couple of times.

So I designed, printed and tested this holder and I really like it.

PLA or a similarly strong material is required due to the screw holes I used. ABS might fall apart in between the layers and I'm NOT responsible when you ruin your expensive phone with this! BE WARNED! THIS IS NOT A GOOD IDEA IN GENERAL! But it works for me. :)

The piece is designed to be a tight fit. For some reason my printer has a scaling problem, so I had to add some hot glue in order to fit my phone nicely. This also prevents the phone from vibrating.

I used 4pc 3x20mm screws as well as 6pc 3x12mm screws to put the holder together. I also bought some silicone matt from IKEA (usually used to put a pot on a table - see pictures), cut the squares off on one side and used it to secure the complete mount on the handle bar using two big zipties.

Not waterproof!

The arms are then trimmed to a length of your choosing. The one pictured is trimmed so that from motor shaft to motor shaft (crossed) is 600mm. The original Square Tubing Quadcopter came out to be 1918 grams with battery and FPV gear. The Poplar Square version comes out to be 1516 grams with the same gear and battery. xcopterCalc sheet:

I got my kids a LitttleBits Smart home Kit and I wanted to create a project to integrate the LittleBits Cloudbit and servo with our Amazon Echo, and 3D Printing (of course!) I used the IFTTT cloud service to integrate Amazon Echo to trigger the LittleBits Cloudbit that activates the LittleBits servo, that in turns turns the spindle of the 3D printed candy dispenser to drop the treats down to the tray.

For the clear plastic hopper, I reused the container from those Fruit Jelly treats I got at the local Asian grocery store (If you can't find it locally, here's something similar on Amazon: http://amzn.com/B003TH0C5O).

3D Print Parts

  1. Download the five STL "Thing Files" from here.
  2. Print CD-Body.stl: I used supports, no brim, 0% infill, 1mm walls on a Lulzbot Taz5 with red PLA.
  3. Print CD-Catch-Tray.stl: no supports, no brim, 10% infill, 1mm walls with red PLA.
  4. Print CD-Spindle.stl: I used supports, no brim, 10% infill, 1mm walls with black PLA.
  5. Print CD-Spindle-Cap-v2.stl: I used supports, no brim, 10% infill, 1mm walls with black PLA.
  6. Print CD-Servo-Bracket.stl: I wanted the bracket stiffer, so I used 15% infill, supports, no brim, 1mm walls with black PLA.

Assemble LittleBits Circuit

Assemble the LittleBits circuit as in the photo below. Any time the circuit receives a signal through the cloudBit, the servo is activated. The servo is attached to the CD-Spindle-Cap. When the servo turns, a few treats drop out of the container and into the tray. You can adjust the spindle hole accordingly depending on how many treats should be dispensed each time.

You can activate the servo remotely in a couple different ways. You can either use the littleBits button in Cloud Control to send a single pulse to the cloudBit, activating the servo. Or, you could use an IFTTT channel, like Date & Time to automate the feeding at times you set, or trigger IFTTT using voice command via an Amazon Echo (details below).

You'll need:
4x 624 bearings

description.text:
This is a rat/mouse nose for costumes. Dimensions are approx 1.5" wide by 1" tall by .5" deep

I print this in ABS:
Extruder: 235
Bed: 110
Infill: 20%
L.Height: .2mm
Feedrate: 60
Travel: 80

I've grown fond of openSCAD.  It's a very nice package and free.  A single line of code constructs a spherical Christmas ornament.
Difference() {sphere(r=25,$fn=48); sphere(r=24,$fn=48); }
The above line makes a hollow sphere about 2 inches across with 1 mm thick walls.  A few additional lines of code builds a connector so that it can be hung on a tree.  The resulting stl file takes about an hour to print and produces a smooth, light, (about 6 grams), ornament.  Unfortunately, while printing, the extruder moves back and forth from the same vertical line leaving a small slit at the midpoint of the sphere.  To get a complete sphere a slightly thicker wall is needed.  The file  "sphere_plus.stl", has a 2 mm wall and takes about two hours to print.  The openSCAD file sphere_plus.scad was used to create it. The image at the upper left shows two complete spheres and the 1 mm sphere with a slit.  I apologise for the colors, I have only yellow and brown plastic left. Silver might be nice. 
Its easy to go further and construct spheres with patterns of holes and with surface decorations.   The method used here is to draw "rays" that start at the center of the sphere and pass through the surface.  The rays can be cylinders or extruded patterns. If one uses openSCAD's difference command holes are made in the surface of the sphere.  Alternatively if one uses union and intersection commands patterns are left on the sphere's surface. I've done some experiments to try and determine what looks best: how many holes, what shapes, etc so this is work in progress.   Here are the results of two such trials.
"Sphere_holes.stl", contains star shaped holes and was made using the difference command. 
"Sphere_star.stl" has star shaped images on its surface and was made using union and intersection commands. See images at left.  
Both use  essentially the same openSCAD code.  A single command needs to be changed to make either holes or decorations. See the comments in make_ornaments.scad.

These spherical models need external support in order to print.  I find the support structures almost as interesting as the models and have included them with the images of the spheres.
I had some initial problems with the spheres pulling away from the supports but when I leveled the build platform all worked well.
Sphere_star.stl has 1 mm walls and 0.75 mm decorations and takes about 90 minutes to print. 
Sphere_holes.stl has 2 mm walls and a complicated support structure.  It takes a bit over two hours to print.  With 1 mm walls it prints in under two hours but is very fragile.  However the slit problem that occurs with the 1 mm complete sphere is not present.  Look near the end of make_ornaments.scad to set the wall thickness.

title: Milsig CQC paintball marker remote air adapter

description.text:
Paintballers!! Woodsballers!! This is a work in progress. This adapter is to slide onto the rear of the Milsig M17 CQC paintball marker and allow a remote line adapter to slide through it AND allow the rear buttstock to be used. The interlock is to allow for the length needed to really make this work on a fully extended stock. Tested on the field and it works great!!! But I need to get some time to put it together and make the full length piece.

update 27Dec. Happy Holidays all! Here's a slight update to the adapter. I've meshed a few of the pieces together to create this base. smoothed out some edges for smoother fitment and to strengthen the edges/ends. I'm printing it now at a high infill as the strong base. I found that the end w/ the cutouts were fairly weak especially on a buttstock with woodsball action. I did break my first iteration of this on the field after bullying it hard for awhile.

prints well and fits great. there's a lil bit of wiggle but at 0.25/75% it is pretty sturdy. much more so that my original. I'll fix up a printable extension soon I hope!

update 01jan here's a few pics of the adapter mated together and fitted to my m17. There's some jiggle room. i did take a lighter to the tips and melded them together. The tips got soft and was able to bend them in a bit for a more snug fit. the slide end works great. the extension file you may want to extend a bit, but up to you. as it is works great at minimal and full extension of the buttstock. I did take a heatgun to the base and extension puzzle connections to fit. they work as they are its up to you if you want to glue them together. enjoy! oh that scope and laser is on there just for tacticoolness!! :)
very slowly!!
